–Female":"1385–Overleden","1380–1480":"1380–1480","1380–1485":"1380–1485","1386–1470":"1386–1470","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1355–Male":"1355–Overleden","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1386":"1386","1496":"1496","1485":"1485","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1380":"1380","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Girsby, Yorkshire, England":"Girsby, Yorkshire, England","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, England"},"en":{"1355–":"1355–Deceased","1355–Female":"1355–Deceased","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1380–1480":"1380–1480","1380–1485":"1380–1485","1386–1470":"1386–1470","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1355–Male":"1355–Deceased","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1386":"1386","1496":"1496","1485":"1485","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1380":"1380","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Girsby, Yorkshire, England":"Girsby, Yorkshire, England","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ellis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Elis</i>, an Old French vernacular form of <i>Elias</i>, the Latin and New Testament Greek form of Hebrew <i>Eliyahu</i>; see   Elijah   and compare   Elias  ,   Lias  ,   Ely  .","English: possibly in some instances from the Middle English female personal name <i>Elice</i>, a pet form of   Elizabeth  .","Welsh: from <i>Elis</i>, a shortened form of the Welsh personal name <i>Elisse</i> (earlier <i>Elisedd</i>, a derivative of <i>elus</i> ‘kindly, benevolent’). As usual in Welsh, the stress in <i>Elisse</i> is on the penultimate syllable <i>-li-</i>, which shifts to initial <i>El-</i> when the name is shortened to <i>Elis</i>. It later became confused with <i>Ellis</i> in 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellison","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name   Ellis   (Old Testament <i>Elijah</i>) + <i>-son</i>.","English: from the Middle English, Old French female personal name <i>Elissent, Elisant</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Elisind</i>.","Scottish: sometimes a post-medieval variant of   Allison  , which is mainly concentrated in northern England and southwestern Scotland. There is a similar Scottish variation between <i>Alison</i> and <i>Elison</i> as female personal names."]},{"name":"Ely","meanings":["English: habitational name from Ely, a cathedral city on an island in the fens north of Cambridge, so named from Old English <i>ǣl</i> ‘eel’ + <i>gē</i> ‘district’.","English, French, and Breton (Finistère): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Elie</i>, <i>Hely</i> (<i>Elijah</i> in the King James Bible); see   Ellis   and   Elias  .","English: variant of   Healey  ."]},{"name":"Eales","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Ellis  , or, alternatively, a variant of   Ell  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Devon the name may also be a variant of <b>Heales</b>, with loss of initial <i>H-</i>, itself a variant of   Heal   or <b>Heel</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, or a variant of   Hales  ."]},{"name":"Elcock","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>(H)elecoc</i>, commonly a pet form of <i>(H)elie</i>, itself a pet form of   Ellis   (from Latin <i>Elias</i>), but sometimes also a Middle English pet form of the female name   Ellen   + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i>."]},{"name":"Elliott","meanings":["English: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Eliot</i>, a pet form of the Old Testament name <i>Elijah</i>, rendered in Greek as <i>Ēlias</i> and in Old French as <i>Élie</i> + the diminutive suffix <i>-ot</i>; compare   Ellis  . The name   Aylett   may in some cases also have been confused with or absorbed into <i>Elliott</i>.","Scottish: late variant of   Elwood  .","Scottish (of Breton origin): perhaps, as some members of the Elliott clan believe, a Scottish variant of the Breton surname <b>Elleouet</b>, a habitational name from one of the hamlets named Allegot in Finistère."]},{"name":"Bellis","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Elisedd</i> ‘son of <i>Elisedd</i>’ (see   Ellis  ).","English: possibly also a nickname from <i>bellis</i>, the regular form of <i>bellows</i> until the 16th century (see   Bellows  ). The form <i>bellis</i> persisted generally until the 16th century and much later in various dialects.","Italian: patronymic from the personal name   Bello  . It is formed with the Latin ablative plural suffix <i>-is</i> imparting the broader sense ‘belonging to, of’, in this case ‘member of the Belli family’ (compare   Belli  ). Compare also   De Bellis  ."]},{"name":"Elles","meanings":["English: variant either of   Ellis   or   Ells  .","Dutch and German: variant of   Ellens  ."]},{"name":"Elijah","meanings":["Welsh, Jewish, and African American: from the personal name <i>Elijah</i>, the usual English transliteration in the King James Bible of the Hebrew name <i>Eliyahu</i> ‘Jehovah is God’, the name of an Old Testament prophet (compare   Elias  ,   Ellis  ). As a Welsh surname, this is a comparatively late adoption of the personal name, adopted after Old Testament personal names became popular among Nonconformists."]},{"name":"Ells","meanings":["English (London and Kent): variant of   Ellis  , or a variant of   Ell  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":100,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Ellis was born in 1355, in Combe Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom. He married Alianor Russell. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in Devon, England."},"et":{"1355–":"1355–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1380–1480":"1380–1480","1380–1485":"1380–1485","1386–1470":"1386–1470","1435–1496":"1435–1496","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1386":"1386","1496":"1496","1485":"1485","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1380":"1380","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Girsby, Yorkshire, England":"Girsby, Yorkshi